<HEADLINE>
<P>
AIR BY JAMES DICKEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Air, much greater than the sea -- 
</P>
<P>
More basic, more human than the sea: all that air 
</P>
<P>
Is calm: 
</P>
<P>
unpeopled, wearing the high lucidity 
</P>
<P>
Of vigil. Maybe one day the mere surface 
</P>
<P>
Of the earth will feel you. 
</P>
<P>
But the air 
</P>
<P>
You can never keep doesn't know 
</P>
<P>
When it lived in your chest: 
</P>
<P>
Mindless, nerveless, breathless, 
</P>
<P>
The air glitters 
</P>
<P>
All the outside, and keeps carrying 
</P>
<P>
You from within. 
</P>
<P>
From the poem, "Immortals," excerpted from "The Eagle's Mile" by James Dickey 
(University Press of New England: $20; $9.95, paper; 65 pp.). "What I looked 
for here," Dickey says about this collection, "was a flicker of light 'from 
another direction,' and when I caught it -- or thought I did -- I have followed 
where it went, for better or worse." 1990 by James Dickey. Reprinted by 
permission of the publisher. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Transcript 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA110490-0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 302671 </DOCID>
