<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING BRIEFING: IT'S NOT ALL THAT IT SEEMS BEHIND SCENES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TED BROCK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In his new book, "Pond Scum and Vultures," Times staff writer Gene 
Wojciechowski documents the often less-than-glamorous lifestyles of his 
sportswriting colleagues. 
</P>
<P>
Wojciechowski tells the story of New York Times writer Michael Janofsky, who 
once worked for the Baltimore Evening Sun, where he covered several Oriole 
games. 
</P>
<P>
At a restaurant one evening, Janofsky spotted Oriole Manager Earl Weaver and 
his wife across the room. Both men finished eating at about the same time. 
</P>
<P>
Janofsky, paid his check, walked outside and gave the valet his parking slip. 
Weaver and his wife soon came out. 
</P>
<P>
Wojciechowski writes: "Figuring this would be a nice time to reintroduce 
himself to Weaver, Janofsky moved toward the manager and extended his hand. 
Weaver looked at Janofsky, reached into his pocket, pulled out a ticket stub 
and said, 'It's the white Cadillac.' " 
</P>
<P>
Trivia time: Which NFL team holds the record for most overtime games played in 
one regular season? 
</P>
<P>
Why?: From Associated Press: "New York Yankee manager Stump Merrill said Friday 
he would like to see George Steinbrenner get involved with running the club 
again some day." 
</P>
<P>
Man coverage: You remember McArthur towels, the company that contracted with 
NFL Properties to provide 2,100 terry-cloth robes and wraps for players, 
following the recent round of female-reporters-in-the-locker-room debates. 
</P>
<P>
Seems the company manufactured them in one size. Trouble is, one size doesn't 
fit all. 
</P>
<P>
Said Greg McArthur, the company's executive vice-president: "The Green Bay 
Packers' equipment manager called and said the terry wrappers we sent weren't 
large enough to fit five of their 300-pound players." 
</P>
<P>
Or thereabouts. The Packer roster lists one 300-pounder, tackle Tony Mandarich, 
and five others at 285 or more. 
</P>
<P>
Zone coverage: The NFL has shipped ten tons of officially licensed merchandise, 
including football jerseys, towels, caps, sun visors, sunglasses, sweatbands 
and copies of its printed products -- such as GameDay magazine, Prolog magazine 
and Pro Set trading cards -- to U.S. military personnel in the Persian Gulf. 
</P>
<P>
Said NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue: "This is our way of bringing a little 
piece of home into their lives at a very trying time." 
</P>
<P>
Bo knows she knows Bo: In an interview for today's Parade magazine, Bo Jackson 
talked about growing up without his dad. 
</P>
<P>
Said Jackson: "My mom is my dad. She's the only mom and dad I know. Whenever 
she needs me, I don't care what I'm doing, I'm gonna drop it and go to her, 
'cause that's all that matters. 
</P>
<P>
"We never had enough food. But at least I could beat on other kids and steal 
their lunch money and buy myself something to eat. But I couldn't steal a 
father's hug when I needed one. I couldn't steal a father's whipping when I 
needed one." 
</P>
<P>
Bo, Derrick both know: Jackson, who led the Kansas City Royals this season with 
28 home runs, returns to town as a Raider today. 
</P>
<P>
Bo and Chief linebacker Derrick Thomas, who played against each other when 
Jackson was at Auburn and Thomas was at Alabama, will face off again. 
</P>
<P>
The Raiders-Chiefs game has been sold out for a month, and Thomas told Dick 
Brinster of the Associated Press: "The intensity (in Missouri) reminds me of 
the Alabama-Auburn rivalry when the whole state shuts down prior to the game. I 
get the same feeling I used to get just before the Alabama-Auburn game every 
year." 
</P>
<P>
Slug here: The Green Bay Packers, with five in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
Quotebook: Chicago Bull Coach Phil Jackson, on the score-happy Denver Nuggets: 
"I think they're playing defense on the wrong end." TED BROCK 
