177 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
A TIP OF THE HAT TO COUNTRY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RANDY LEWIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
** 1/2 GARTH BROOKS "No Fences" Capitol 
</P>
<P>
Garth Brooks' 1989 debut album was not only a hit in country circles, but 
climbed the pop charts with surprising ease -- especially for one whose sound 
is thoroughly traditional. 
</P>
<P>
The Oklahoma native's follow-up has been doing a similar leap-frog up the pop 
and country charts. 
</P>
<P>
This one is a considerable improvement artistically, but more because of the 
weaknesses of the first -- which sank musically under the weight of one 
hopelessly melodramatic song after another -- than because of the modest yields 
of the second. 
</P>
<P>
In "Fences' " best moments, Brooks' woody baritone suggests several lifetimes 
of hard living. And he reveals a canny sense of style in a witty swing 
treatment of the Fleetwoods' sappy old hit "Mr. Blue." Still, the album suffers 
overall from as many predictable comeuppances to wrongdoers and rewards for 
do-gooders as an old Gene Autry movie. Give this sophomore effort a split 
decision for a few steps in the right direction and the promise it holds for 
its successor. RANDY LEWIS 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Garth Brooks 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
