<P>
100 DOLPHINS DIE IN ISLAND ROUNDUP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fishermen drove hundreds of dolphins toward shore on an island in southern 
Japan, causing the death of more than 100 of the mammals, a fisheries official 
said. 
</P>
<P>
He said dozens of fishermen drove the dolphins toward Fukuejima, hoping to kill 
some for food. But hundreds became trapped by the receding tide and at least 
100 died on the sand, the official said. Dolphins are taken annually by local 
people because fish and meat are expensive in the isolated community, Kyodo 
News Service reported. 
</P>
